                  </div>
                  <div class="content hide">
                    <div class="wrapper">
                      <p>
                        1. Uganda like many other African Countries has one of the highest returns on investment in the World.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        Return on investment in Uganda is 5.3 % as opposed to 2.3 % in the US. 
                        The 5.3 % return on Investment in Uganda is expected to skyrocket to 7 % in the near future due to the massive investment in critical infrastructure.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        2. Uganda is the fastest growing economy in the East African Community with a GDP of over $ 40.43 Billion (WB, 2021). GDP forecast for 2023, 6.2 % (Fisher, Q2 2023)
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        3. Uganda’s stable and consistent Macroeconomic policies, proximity as a logistics hub within the Great Lakes region and increased regional trade have contributed to a consistent increase in FDI inflows despite Covid – 19 Pandemic. For example from  $ 807 Million in 2019, $ 927.10 Million in 2020 to $ 1.14 Billion in 2021
                      </p>
                      <p style="margin-block-end: 0;">
                        4. The Country’s Economy is very liberalized.
                      </p>
                      <ul style="margin: 0 0 0 4px;">
                        <li style="padding:0;margin:0;">(a) All sectors are open for investment to the private sector.</li>
                        <li style="padding:0;margin:0;">(b) Security of Person and Property is guaranteed</li>
                        <li style="padding:0;margin:0;">(c) Foreign Companies are allowed to have 100 % ownership in Projects.</li>
                      </ul>
                      <p>
                        5. The Country’s Progressive Investment Code makes Uganda one of the most open Countries to private foreign investment.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        6. Low cost of production;
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        For example Uganda has the lowest labor Cost in the East African Community region; the Average yearly wage for unskilled production operative is $ 440.
                      </p>
                      <p style="margin-block-end: 0;">
                        7. Ugandan goods and services have a large domestic, regional and Global Markets (Quota and Tariffs free);
                      </p>
                      <ul style="margin: 0 0 0 4px;">
                        <li style="padding:0;margin:0;">(a) East African Community – 300 Million People</li>
                        <li style="padding:0;margin:0;">(b) COMESA – 600 Million People</li>
                        <li style="padding:0;margin:0;">(c) AFCTA – 1.3 Billion People, in 55 Countries with a Combined GDP of $ 3.5 Trillion</li>
                        <li style="padding:0;margin:0;">(d) EU EBA (Everything Except Arms)</li>
                        <li style="padding:0;margin:0;">(e) AGOA – 6,000 Products</li>
                      </ul>
                      <p>
                        8. Uganda is the Number 1, Regional leader in Capital Markets growth (Absa Africa, Financial Markets Index 2022)
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        9. Uganda is the Second most bio diverse Country in Africa 202 (UBF). Green Investment and Carbon offset potential.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        10. Best Tourist Destination in the World (CNN, 2023)
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        11. Best Tourist Destination in the whole world (CNN, 2023)
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        12. Most of the Country’s lucrative sectors like tourism are under tapped due to lack of access to cheap financing and skilled work force.
                      </p>
                      <p>
                        13. Country’s Pan Africanism is currently focused on prioritizing the economic empowerment of Africans and the African diaspora.
                      </p>
